{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613135"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:30:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:30:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16303"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16303"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.16,0.56,0.28,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8994"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74628"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8994"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16303"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60122"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7502"},{"type":"tags","id":"8561"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21412"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21414"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74628"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe inner ear contains specialised sensory regions that detect different types of head movement and position.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures contains the crista ampullaris sensory receptor?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Macula of utricle","Macula of saccule","Ampulla of semicircular canals","Organ of Corti","Cupula"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eampulla of semicircular canals\u003C/strong\u003E contains the crista ampullaris, which is the sensory receptor that detects angular acceleration of the head. The crista ampullaris consists of hair cells embedded in a gelatinous structure called the cupula.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emacula of utricle\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Emacula of saccule\u003C/strong\u003E are different sensory regions that detect linear acceleration and head position relative to gravity. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eorgan of Corti\u003C/strong\u003E is the sensory receptor for hearing in the cochlea. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecupula\u003C/strong\u003E is the gelatinous structure that covers the crista ampullaris but is not itself the location of the sensory receptor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEach semicircular canal has an enlarged region called the ampulla which houses the crista ampullaris. When the head rotates, movement of endolymph causes deflection of the cupula, which bends the hair cells and triggers nerve impulses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The crista ampullaris contains hair cells that detect rotational head movements in the semicircular canals.","The crista ampullaris is located specifically in the ampulla, a dilated portion of each semicircular canal.","Different vestibular organs have specialised sensory regions - cristae in semicircular canals and maculae in the otolith organs."],"references":["Rabbitt RD. Semicircular canal biomechanics in health and disease. J Neurophysiol. 2019 Mar 1;121(3):732-755. doi: 10.1152/jn.00708.2018. Epub 2018 Dec 19. PMID: 30565972; PMCID: PMC6520623","S\u00e1nchez L\u00f3pez de Nava A, Lasrado S. Physiology, Ear. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK540992/","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60122"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16303"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60122"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T23:17:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T00:02:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8994"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74628"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synony